HEADWORD: Skulk
<hw>Skulk</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Skulked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Skulking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Of Scand. origin; cf. Dan.
<ets>skulke</ets> to spare or save one's self, to play the truant, Sw.
<ets>skolka</ets> to be at leisure, to shirk, Icel. <ets>skolla</ets>.
Cf. <er>Scowl</er>.]</ety> <def>To hide, or get out of the way, in a
sneaking manner; to lie close, or to move in a furtive way; to
lurk.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Want <xex>skulks</xex> in holes and crevices.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>W. C. Bryant.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Discovered and defeated of your prey,⟦br⟧
You <qex>skulked</qex> behind the fence, and sneaked away.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

